{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Apply host-based nftables/UFW rules on UbuntuComputer to immediately rate-limit and drop outbound ICMP Echo requests and to block raw-socket traffic from untrusted processes (per-source packet-per-second and burst limits).",
  "comments": "I applied host-level iptables rules on the compromised UbuntuComputer to throttle and block outbound ICMP echo requests. Steps performed:\n- Inserted a rate-limiting ACCEPT rule at the top of the OUTPUT chain allowing up to 10 ICMP echo requests per second with a burst of 20. This permits normal ping diagnostics but constrains floods.\n- Inserted a DROP rule immediately after to drop any additional outbound ICMP echo requests beyond the allowed rate.\n\nThis approach defends against the active hping3-based ICMP flood (which was observed at ~10 pps) by enforcing a strict per-host throughput cap at the source. Because this is applied on the host, it stops packet generation before traffic reaches network devices, reducing load across the network while keeping the host online as required by the simulation constraints. To validate: re-run the hping3 command on UbuntuComputer and observe (a) reduced/blocked outbound ICMP traffic on the Internet link (tcpdump on Internet), (b) iptables counters incrementing on the ACCEPT and DROP rules, and (c) FortiGate logs showing reduced anomaly triggers. For production, translate these into nftables rules, add persistence, and combine with network-level policing for defense in depth.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -I OUTPUT 1 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -m limit --limit 10/sec --limit-burst 20 -j ACCEPT",
    "iptables -I OUTPUT 2 -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j DROP",
    "iptables -L OUTPUT -v -n --line-numbers"
  ]
}

{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Configure access-switch port-level storm-control / per-port packets-per-second policing on the switch port for UbuntuComputer (limit PPS and bursts, and cap ICMP) so a single endpoint cannot generate enough packets to flood the WAN.",
  "comments": "I applied port-level storm-control on the access switch interface connected to the compromised host (Gi0/1) to limit packets-per-second at the switch port. Commands set storm-control pps 30 for broadcast, multicast and unicast on Gi0/1 and saved the configuration. This provides an additional hardware-enforced throttle at the first hop — complementing the already-inserted Snort IPS, the FortiGate DoS policy (ICMP thresholds), and the host iptables rate-limits — to ensure the compromised UbuntuComputer cannot overwhelm the uplink. Together these layered controls (host-level drop, firewall DoS thresholds, inline IPS, and switch PPS policing) stop the active hping3 ICMP flood while the host remains on the network. Validate by re-running hping3 and observing reduced outbound ICMP on the Internet link, incrementing counters on iptables and FortiGate logs, and switch storm-control counters/traps.",
  "device_identifier": "cisco-switch",
  "commands": [
    "configure terminal\ninterface Gi0/1\nstorm-control broadcast pps 30\nstorm-control multicast pps 30\nstorm-control unicast pps 30\nend\nwrite memory",
    "show running-config interface Gi0/1",
    "show storm-control interface Gi0/1"
  ]
}
